<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO JULIA</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar 25 22:02:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Julia,<br><br>
The experience of returning home from Vietnam was, in some ways, as damaging a psychological experience as some experiences of combat. At least in combat, the enemy was honorable in ways understood among soldiers, and the rules brutal but devistatingly fair. Kill or be killed is a very simple concept. Those of us who survived and ran the ennervating gauntlet of &quot;haircut fetish low-brow lifer rear echelon E-6's&quot; on our way out to freedom were faced with another entrapment of a form with which few of us were prepared to deal, much less understand.<br><br>
In the span of a few short days, much of which was spent in the gloomy windowless and airless outprocessing caverns at Oakland, CA, with its endless shuffling rows and columns and the frustratingly slow creep to the doors to the street, and to freedom, we were transformed from jungle reflex soldiers to jungle reflex civilians. We hit the streets in Class A uniforms, and the streets hit back.<br><br>
My recollection of my first steps through those doors into real daylight is one of ambush by people spitting, yelling, and shouting epithets. &quot;Baby killer&quot; was the favorite slogan. Taxi cabs were plentiful. They became mobile foxholes of security as we got out of there as fast as we could. If we had weapons, I know there were some who would have used them.<br><br>
The first meal in freedom at the hotel, awaiting the next day and our flights home, was another ambush. We were denied service because the hotel manager did not want any fights in his establishment. We were in no mood to fight, but it appeared to us that the rules had changed. He compensated by sending food to our rooms, free. That was just great. I already began to acquire the taste of a leper.<br><br>
The flight home was a memorable trip. Fellow passengers in my row always found other seats. I always had plenty of room, but no company. Two stewardeses moved me once into a deserted first class. That was the first and last act of kindness or respect I experienced then to now.<br><br>
I found &quot;home&quot; to be a place of quiet denial and indifference, the silence punctuated by the occasional sharp words of anguish from those who lost family, and wished you had been killed instead.<br><br>
I went back to school. My roommate was a Canadian, a real great guy. We got along just fine. He confided in me one day that he was asked by campus housing if he minded a Vietnam Veteran as a roomate. No American wanted to room with me. Vietnam Veterans had the nasty habit of sleepwalking and brandishing knives in the dead of night, as the story went.<br><br>
From here, the rest is another story, but I can summarize by saying that I truly understood the feeling of &quot;sitting in the back of the bus&quot;.<br><br>
These are the recollections of a few of my personal experiences. Please feel free to use these words in any way helpful to you. <br><br>
Arthur<br>

